A rigid lump has been squeezed between two plates, one of which is moving at velocity $v_1$ and the other at $v_2$. At the given moment, velocities are horizontal and the contact points of the lump and plates are aligned. In the figure, mark all points of the lump with velocity modulus equal to $v_1$ or $v_2$.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=5cm]{kalda_plate_lump.png}
\end{center}

solution:
We use the idea of instantaneous center of rotation. Rotation means perpednicular velocities from the lines from the center. Thus, the center must lie on the dashed line. Specifically, it will lie in a ratio $\frac{v_1}{v_1+v_2}L$ from the top if $L$ is the distance between the plates. Then, the points on the lump with the same velocity are:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item For $v_1$: a circle of radius $\frac{v_1}{v_1+v_2}L$ centered at ${v_1}{v_1+v_2}L$ from the top.
        \item For $v_2$: a circle of radius $\frac{v_2}{v_1+v_2}L$ centered at ${v_1}{v_1+v_2}L$ from the top.
    \end{itemize}

